# Product Description

Our final product will be two things primarily, an n64 compiled to web assembly such that it can run in a web browser and a mod for sm64 with custom levels, enemies, and other content. The goal is to have a user provide the sm64 rom to the website, then patch the mod into the rom for easy playability.

### Major Features to Implement:
- A custom courtyard hub world to replace the castle hub world in vanilla sm64, paintings to worlds will be replaced by custom portals (wells, waterfalls, etc.)
- 3 custom levels with unique objectives  
- At least 1 custom enemy for each level
- A simple storyline

### Stretch  goals we hope to implement:
- 4th custom level  
- Custom Powerups  
- Boss battle(s) (preferably for each level, but most likely for the 3rd or 4th)  
- Additional custom enemies

# Use Cases

1) **Murad** | Actors:  
   1) The player of the Mod, who will be performing player actions such as running, jumping, and completing objectives
      1) This is technically separate from b, as one can play the Mod without actually using the website-emulator
   2) The user of the Website, who will be interacting with the emulator
2) **Michael** | Triggers:   
   1) User loading the ISO causes the wasm emulator to patch the mod into it and launch the game  
   2) User triggers loading custom levels through making contact with objects in the hub world, the rest of the game runs like vanilla sm64 with new enemies and environments  
3) **Osama** | Preconditions  
   1) ROM must be uploaded by the user  
   2) Mod files must be present in the server files for patching  
   3) Website must be on and running under its appropriate domain  
4) **Daksh** | Postconditions (success scenario)  
   1) The mod must be patched with the ROM after execution so that it is executable directly  
   2) Emulator must be presently running the patched ROM  
5) **Murad** | List of steps (success scenario)  
   1) Website needs to patch the given ROM with the internal mod folder  
   2) The website then needs to employ its built in emulator in order for the user to actually play the game  
6) **Osama** | Extensions/variations of the success scenario  
   1) Emulator converted to WASM runs but with poor performance compared to a regular installation  
   2) Mod runs but has poor performance due to a lack of optimisation/high poly count/unknown factors  
   3) Mod runs and can technically be completed but has an unwanted amount of bugs that make the player experience nonoptimal  
7) **Michael** | Exceptions: failure conditions and scenarios  
   1) WASM emulator fails to load due to browser compatibility or other issues  
   2) ISO fails to load, mod is not patched and nothing runs in the emulator  
   3) Mod does not patch into ROM, default SM64 ROM is loaded or nothing is loaded at all  
   4) Bugs or corruptions occur when patching that cause game to crash or not function properly  
   5) Bugs or corruptions within the mod even after patching successfully cause the game to crash or not function properly

# Non-functional Requirements

### Scalability:
- The website must be able to handle multiple users at once (10-100), this shouldn’t be a huge concern since wasm will be running locally

### Usability:
- Website must be able to conveniently patch a user-given rom with a server-stored copy of the mods files. After this patching, the website must then emulate the patched rom
- Website must account for keyboard controls since it will primarily be ran from a PC
- Actual mod contents must be completable from beginning to end
- Wasm emulator must be compatible with multiple browsers
- Performance must be smooth when running any compatible n64 game

### Maintainability:
- Mod must be further updated and patched to remove any bugs and glitches
- Domain names and websites must be continuously supported monetarily so that the website remains online and usable

# External Requirements

Relevant domain names and websites must be set up in order for users to actually connect to the website. Similarly, the mod files must be available independently if one were to want to download the assets separate from the web-emulation.

The actual mod must account for all the abilities of the player, ensuring that any user-input and actions doesn’t result in errors and fault.
